message: My ONLY suggestion would be to put the tylenol / excedrin...motrin...whatever kind of pill in either a pill case or bottle (labeled), with the amount of the recommended dosage. In times of crisis, we must remember that ODing does not equal less pain or a solution. A simple way to avoid this is having only the recommended amount available during these times. A phone number list is always a good call (no pun intended) too! At LEAST 10, in case people cant pick up or are busy. I usually include a few crisis lines in mine to know ill always have someone to talk to. But they come after the people who know me personally.

We call them 'distraction boxes' rather than crisis kits. I like things with different textures, smells, sounds etc. Lots of written notes to oneself .. reminders of things you have got through, funnies, kind things people have said about you, compliments and achievements. Whatever the things are that make you feel content and plenty of colouring, crosswords, games. Scrabble tiles are good So is bubblewrap to pop.

My someone very close to me is on a 48 hour hold. He was getting ready to go gas himself in his truck with a hose in the exhaust. He has been going through a bad breakup with the mother of his daughter and things came to a very bad escalation point. She talked him into seeking help by leading him to believe they could have a chance again, but I don't believe this is what she really wants as her actions speak otherwise. I am very worried for his safety in the very near future. 
But here is a bigger question. If someone is in so much pain throughout their whole life, has been in and out of Doctor's offices and psych wards and on and off of meds, tries to cope everyday but just can't do it, can't bear to live another day in their excruciating existence, can't take the fighting and the drama and the crushing weight of the world anymore, is it wrong to force someone into a locked ward "for their own good" because we are too selfish about how we would feel to have him end his life on his own terms when he finally comes to the realization that this is all too much to handle anymore and he is tired of running on a treadmill to nowhere? Is it his fault for wanting to die, or is it our fault for not wanting them to go? I always have maintained that I just want him to be happy and not have these feelings anymore. I want him to not be burdened by the depression or the anxiety or the fear. But what if that never happens. What if this trip to the psych ward doesn't help again? What if they can't stop what his mind is telling him? What if he again reaches the decision that the only way to stop the madness is to end his life? It it right to take that decision away from him and lock him up and "keep him safe" because we are too selfish to be able to let him go? We never want anyone to die, ever. When my grandma was in the hospital after falling again at 84 and injuring her hip for the second time, we didn't want her to die. She was skin and bones, moaning in pain with a fentynol patch on each skinny arm, and the Dr. said all they could really do was keep her comfortable. My grandma had a DNR order. She did not want to be kept alive in that situation. None of us wanted for her to have to leave us but it was the only way for her pain to end. What if sometimes the only way for someone to finally have peace is to let them go and know that the time we shared with them is special? Where is the line between free will and control of your destiny, and controlling another person's life because you may not like the outcome?

I have had treatment resistant Major Depressive Disorder since I was 15. I also have very bad Generalized Anxiety Disorder with panic attacks. I've been on so many cocktails of meds and have even received ECT. I don't understand why meds don't help like they should. The combination I'm on now is the best I've ever been on, but I still feel suicidal at least once a week. I've attempted once and used to cut...rarely do now. My therapist is the best one I've ever had since I was 15...I'm almost 33 years old. My 3 year old daughter keeps me here, but i can't control my brain. My husband has FMLA, so he comes home when I'm feeling suicidal. It is the most excruciating pain that only people who have been in that state of mind can possibly understand. Even though I don't really have hope...nothing else they really can do for me...God has kept me here somehow. This quote somewhat gives me hope, "Just when the caterpillar thought her world was over, she became a butterfly.". Every single one of you matter and everyone lost to these horrible diseases MATTER. Alessia Cara is one of the most talented young musicians to have come up in the last decade, and to have her connected to such a worthy cause is amazing.  I remember being very trepidatious about calling the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline because of a terrible experience I had with another suicide hotline in the past (one that was touted by the PostSecret project), but the person I talked to in my first call was so kind, compassionate, and understanding that they carried me through a really dark and lonely night (my depression was being triggered by my mom's passing that day).  In future calls this hotline has been there for me and even though I don't need it anymore, I'm happy it'll always be there for others who do and just in case I might need it in the future.  Thank y'all for providing this service, and thanks so much to Ms. Cara for lending her voice and talents to this cause.

I still have a really hard time wearing anything but long sleeves and pants. I've been struggling with self harm for 13 years. I can't wear women's shorts because they're too short, and the scars on my arms and thighs are the worst. Every part of my body has at least one (or a few dozen) scars. It's horrible when people just stare and then look away or act as if I would hurt someone else because I hurt myself. I'm working on getting cover ups, but even now employers aren't fond of tattoos. It's a really big lose-lose situation for me.

A couple years ago I decided to stop lying about my scars and to just be honest about how they got there. I may have created these scars but they do not define me and are only part of my history. As the years have gone on, I have found many other people also have their own battle scars and find comfort knowing they are not alone. I think being honest with others helps keep the conversations going and maybe someday they too will be able to talk about it so openly. The more we can talk, the easier it will be to reach out for the help when needed, I think.

For the most part, I don't mind mine. They're just there and my doctor said they'll eventually fade more over time. I, more often than not, mind the things my friends say to me (or don't) when they see them. I see their side-glances of "oh shit what is that" or their looks of confusion. (I would rather them just straight out ask me rather than blatantly staring). 

I actually went to the dermatologist for prescription-strength scar fade cream and him and his staff gave me the most disgusting response. Basically the nurse had to leave the room because she couldn't stand the sight of my scars and the reason why I was there. My doctor then proceeded to lecture me on god and how he didn't understand what I was doing to myself. This is why there is a stigma and this is why people are so hesitant to talk about it, because of experiences like these. I told him why and explained everything and that if he had more questions he could go read an article on Psychology Today. 

That being said, I just put cover-up on them now and don't go to that doctor anymore lol. It's a part of my life I'm not particularly proud of, but we all have moments like those. Just gotta keep going and keep fighting because it's just not worth it.

It's really good we're sharing articles about this kind of stuff and getting what has lived in the darkness of so many people's lives out in the open. I remember throughout my years every occasion that someone I knew (or even a total stranger in a store aisle) looked at the scars on my arm and said, "What happened there?" And then everyone else turn to look as well, and now you're faced with that incredibly uncomfortable moment of feeling embarrassed, ashamed, frustrated that they would ask that...and you have to decide do I lie and tell them, "Nothing happened." or "I broke up a cat fight." to save their comfort or do I tell them, "I had a bad relapse and cut myself open and ended up in the hospital." ? It's not a pleasant situation to have that thrown at you unexpectedly and have people pry into something so personal without really wanting to know what happened. I wish people would think a bit before saying something, and least of all, not by thrusting you in the spotlight unannounced.
Hopefully articles like this can spread awareness, and given time, help people to tread more gently when noticing and discussing one's scars. Many are a result of a suicide attempt (s), and to bring that up out with such casualness can be upsetting. It's not always easy to discuss that, usually it's never easy. So tread softly.

I personally do not hide my scars or make any attempt. I don't feel a want to hide them nor do I feel I should hide them to spare other people whatever discomfort they might feel. If what I went through upsets them, not to be rude, but that's their problem. Don't make it mine, please.

I see people notice my scars, I see their eyes, their stares, I notice when they notice. I also notice other people's scars but I make a point to never stare or linger. I see it and I know what it is and my heart instantly goes out to them. I don't know if their battle is done, or if it ever will be, but I see them alive and in the world for another day and I feel it's a small victory.  And in a weird way, it gives me a bit of hope when I see other people with scars, because they've made it so far and so have I and we're still here. We're all still here despite the scars. :)

Walk it alone because your darkness will always burden someone else. Friends won't stick around if you don't bring positive vibes into their lives and its not fair to expect them too.

"Professional" help only cares depending on your health insurance coverage. Sitting with a therapist while they crack you open and spill those emotions from you only to say that'll be $150 when your 45 minutes are up isn't the most caring & satisfying feeling. You're alone while they're on vacation with the money they made from the suffering. 

Learn to walk it alone. Retrain your brain. There is no one out there that will ever care more about you then you. Its not easy, its never easy. 

What is easy is getting stuck in the endless loop of thinking someone is out there who truly cares without any gain or benefit to themselves. Maybe those people do exist but while your trying to find that person, you suffer and the clock ticks away. Before you know it two decades have gone by and you haven't healed and you're still alone. 

The real battle comes from making that ok in your own brain. Making only yourself enough to be happy. Happiness may never find you. It hasnt for me. I may never find it and die one day never truly feeling happy or going a day witbout sadness. But its never easy.

The most important thing you can do for someone who is severely depressed and/or suicidal is LISTEN and watch for the signs of depressive episodes. Don't let loved ones or yourself lay in bed for days, not take meds, eat poorly, get no exercise.  Doctors told me for years until they were blue in the face:  you need to get up and get out. I literally had to force myself. I was dead weight; felt like an elephant was on my back. Also, those struggling with bipolar disorder, watch out for mania. Some of my worst struggles came with manic episodes. Education is so important. Friends and family need to understand this (mostly) invisible illness. Invite family members to therapy or even psychiatric appointments if you are so inclined.  I did this with my father and only then did he start to come around.  Support systems are important.  And talk about it!! If we all can be open and honest about our disease, as if we are talking about diabetes or heart disease, we can change people's perception of the disease.

Been there so many times myself. Here again now. Suicide may seem selfish to those left behind. But I have never wanted to hurt anybody, in fact I've fought it more times than I've attempted it simply because I don't want to hurt anyone. But for me, when I do attempt it, it's because it's so dark, cold, lonely, desperate and incredibly painful that there seems no other way. Fifteen years I've been fighting it. I take tons of meds a day. And have therapies and a carer. In and out of psychiatric units for long periods. It is still incredibly lonely. I am alone with the pain. There may be people around me. But they don't know what's in my mind. 

There's a quote that says 'the bravest thing I ever did, was to continue living when all I wanted to do was die' 

When I am stable I believe that to be true. But when I'm not, and I attempt it, I think I am brave in doing so, because death is even terrifying for those who crave it. Because it is such an unknown end. 

When I am stable I say I live each day like it's my last, because I know it takes only seconds for me to spiral and hit rock bottom.

When a person like me is having really hard times and you try to trust someone you get a lot of religious stuff (I'm a Christian) like God won't give you more than you can handle, your weak,pray, believe your healed, or the other side of the fence, Try using the Emotional Code,heal yourself,try yoga,breathing excerises, there's a lot of garbage out there.people can get wrapped up in it that dont know the difference. When your desperate you'd try anything.Then there's Healers saying from their touch they have Gods power to heal you. I was accosted so bad I had bruises all over my body.I started hemmoraging, bleeding out of 300+ pores face,breast,ears, abdomen back,arms,legs,pelvis. It formed a ring inside flesh,a liquid see thru would leak out touch my skin like acid. Screaming. Small hospital couldn't help. Just me and my doctor over 6 years, plus damage to spine 6 infiltrations every 4 months for excutiated pain, damage in knee/femur painful permanent, and maxillo facial surgery had to remove all teeth,gums,bones all broken. I'm housebound, if I fell I would get 70-100 lesions more. I had no support bc I told 2 friends, it was too much for them,and you shouldn't charge your sister that did that to you for 9 months. So I needed medicine. You get put down for that, finally a specialist called me upon reading my file this year and now my hemmoraging is stopping and I'm not leaking a lot of water from 5 spots on my bad leg. My 3 adult children visit a half hour 3x a year, no support. I don't bother all the groups I was involved in incl. School tutoring, churches etc.no calls from them.I wanted to die, I prayed I died bc I want to have a life. My husband just leaves bedroom door shut, and thinks I can still take care if a 12 1/2 room home. I was so close to my children, I feel I lost them and my man too. I not once had anyone take care of me I did it all myself. When I go to appointment I hide it all so no one knows. I don't want pity. Just a real friend that will hug me and believe in me that I'm trying so hard to get better, at least what I can. I would think that anyone would understand why I don't want to live plus I have 2 muscular diseases I was handling before this happened. I don't want pity just understanding. Its not CIG burns and I'm no druggie that's what the sm hospital said till they were told different. I apologize for the lengthy text..  I just want to be valued as a person. I have started therapy with a specialist in P.T.S.D.  etc.I don't show my family my burdens wrapped in bandages everyday.I understand why a person would want to die. But I have one thing I want to say to them. There's no one like you in this earth. Your valued and wanted bc you have talents,wisdom and knowledge only you can have no one else. If I can save one person from suicide then my life would be worth living. Thanks for listening

Perhaps some of the outcry surrounding this series is society's unwillingness/inability to pull blinders off and face the uncomfortable fact that "my kid" could be a bully, could be a victim, could be a witness and we have no clue about it. Many people are saying this series idealizes revenge and suicide, but I think it gives a very honest look (albeit dramatic) at what our kids are/do/see/feel and this honesty simply makes us uncomfortable. I volunteered at a crisis hotline and didn't watch because the title alone angers me; there may be numerous reasons someone is depressed, but suicide usually boils down to one reason: person wants to end his/her pain. And rarely is it about revenge and "see what you did?" Also, most people don't leave notes, let alone a series of video tapes. And it's never anyone's fault; it's the choice of person ending his/her life... though certainly survivors are left to grapple with the mystery. I'm glad there are more discussions about this important topic, but from what I read I think more accurate portrayals would further the cause better. People at risk may be triggered by the show or decided not to watch, which doesn't help them, and those who wanted to glimpse "what it's like" probably didn't see typical scenarios. But again, I didn't watch.

The Tree Blossom
By Lorena Cuevas 

  All of my favorite flowers grow on trees.  Cherry, plum, fuchsia, and magnolia. I think that not to be a coincidence. One should aspire to be a tree blossom. All come and goes with the season. Beautiful, growing high. They always have hope that tomorrow will be better. Living their whole life knowing that although their are beautiful, that beauty is fickle and fleeting. Beauty which does not last. Like those trees which surround changes with the season. Once colorful and fragrant, one day it could all dissipate, yet still you bloom. 
  Although delicate they are resistant to bad weather. As these flowers, you do not know when the storm is coming. You, yet still survive the bad weather. Every year you try again as if though you forgot about what happened in the last season.  
  Sometimes people will come and spray poison all around you. This poison not only surrounds you but covers you. You yet still, survive the poison. You are surrounded by flowers that are going through the same weather,poison, and uncertainty as you.
   Be a perennial, lasting for a long infinite time. Please do not  forget the flowers that grow on trees can sometimes bear fruit. Never give up on the hope that your efforts will be fruitful. There are festivals all around the world that look forward to a new years blossom. Every year everyone looks foward to your blooms. Please never stop trying to make the world stop for one moment and antisipate you;
